{"title_page": "Steve Fenberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Steve Fenberg\n| image = Steve Fenberg.JPG\n| office = Majority Leader of the [[Colorado Senate]]\n| term_start = January 4, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Chris Holbert]]\n| successor = \n| state_senate1 = Colorado\n| district1 = [[Colorado's 18th Senate district|18th]]\n| term_start1 = January 11, 2017\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Rollie Heath]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|1|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Toledo, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Lindsay Urban\n| education = [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado, Boulder]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| website = {{url|stevefenberg.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Fenberg''' (born January 2, 1984) is an American [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician serving as a [[Colorado Senate|State Senator]] from [[Colorado]], representing the [[Colorado's 18th Senate district|18th district]] since 2017.<ref name=\"CGA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradosenate.org/fenberg |title=Senator Steve Fenberg |location=[[Denver, Colorado]] |publisher=Colorado Senate Democrats |accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref> He currently serves as Senate Majority Leader.\n\n==Education==\nSenator Fenberg received his [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[Environmental Policy]] at the University of Colorado.<ref name =\"DC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/colorado-election-news/ci_30471306/steve-fenberg-state-senate-district-18 |title= Steve Fenberg: State Senate, District 18 |location=Boulder, Colorado |publisher=[[Daily Camera]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017|date= 2016-10-15 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA few years after graduating from CU, Fenberg founded New Era Colorado, a nonprofit organization dedicated engaging, educating, and training young people in the political process. The organization has registered hundreds of thousands of young people to vote in Colorado and successfully passed several pieces of legislation related to election reform, student debt, and climate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neweracolorado.org/about-us/#.WKum7xIrJn4 |title= New Leaders for a Generation |location=Denver, Colorado |publisher=New Era Colorado |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also served on the Board of Directors for ProgressNow, One Colorado Political Committee, and INVST Community Studies as well as the Boulder Housing Working Group and the city of Boulder Capital Improvement Taskforce.<ref name =\"DC\" /> Fenberg now serves as an Advisory Board member for the dZi Foundation, an international nonprofit providing development work in remote areas of Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dzi.org/who-we-are/teams/|title=Teams {{!}} dZi foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\nFenberg is part-owner of the Bread Bar, a cocktail bar in the historic town of [[Silver Plume, Colorado|Silver Plume]]. Bread Bar resides at the site of a historic bakery from the 1800's.<ref name=\"AS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stevefenberg.org/about-steve-2/ |title= About Steve |publisher= 2016 Fenberg State Senate |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>.\n\n==Policy positions==\n===Environment===\nAs an advocate of a statewide [[carbon tax]], Fenberg would also like to increase the [[renewable energy]] standards from 30% to 50% in the next 30 years.\n\nAs far as [[fracking]] is concerned, he acknowledges the risks involved and the need for tighter regulations but is a supporter of local control by communities.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite web |url= http://www.stevefenberg.org/issues/ |title= Current Legislation and Priorities |location=Boulder, Colorado |publisher=2016 Feinberg State Senate |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\nFenberg is [[United States pro-choice movement|pro-choice]] and supports same-sex marriage. He supports funding to expand access to comprehensive birth control.\n\n===Jobs & growth===\nFenberg believes in the right of workers to [[collective bargaining|collectively bargain]], strives for an increased minimum wage and sees the current requirements pertaining to sick days as inadequate.<ref name=\"SS\" />\n\n==Tenure (Colorado Senate)==\nFenberg has served as a member of the following committees:\n\n* Senate Agriculture, Natural Resources, and Energy Committee \n* State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee\n* Legislative Council\n* Executive Committee of the Legislative Council<ref name=\"CGA\" />\n\nAuthored/sponsored bills by Fenberg have focused on a variety of topics ranging from the easing of student debt to gerrymandering reform as well as the prohibition of [[conversion therapy|gay conversion therapy]].<ref name=\"SS\" /> The following bills are some of Fenberg's legislative accomplishments:\n\n=== Energy, Climate, and the Environment ===\n\n* SB19-181: Comprehensive oil & gas reforms to protect health & safety<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-181|title=Protect Public Welfare Oil And Gas Operations {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* SB19-236: Sunset of the Public Utilities Commission <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-236|title=Sunset Public Utilities Commission &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB18-009: Establishing the right of consumers to store their own energy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-009|title=Allow Electric Utility Customers Install Energy Storage Equipment {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* SB18-143: Parks and Wildlife Measures to Increase Revenue <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-143|title=Parks and Wildlife Measures to Increase Revenue &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Election Reform ===\n\n* SB19-235: Creating automatic voter registration<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-235|title=Automatic Voter Registration {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> \n* HB19-1278: Modifications to Uniform Election Code <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1278|title=Modifications to Uniform Election Code &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Human/Civil Rights & Mental Health ===\n\n* HB19-1129: Prohibiting gay conversion therapy on minors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1129|title=Prohibit Conversion Therapy for A Minor {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* HB19-1266: Restore Voting Rights to Parolees <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1266|title=Restore Voting Rights Parolees &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* HB19-1280: Youth Mental Health Education and Suicide Prevention <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1120|title=Youth Mental Health Education and Suicide Prevention &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Hemp & Marijuana ===\n\n* SB19-224: Sunset Regulated Marijuana<ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-224|title=Sunset Regulated Marijuana &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* HB19-1028: Medical Marijuana Condition Autism <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1028|title=Medical Marijuana Condition Autism &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB19-220: Creating statewide plan for hemp cultivation & regulation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-220|title=Hemp Regulation Alignment With 2018 Federal Farm Bill {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\n\n* SB19-002: Regulate Student Loan Servicers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-002|title=Regulate Student Education Loan Servicers &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref> \n* SB19-057: Employee Information Public Student Loan Repayment Programs <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-057|title=Employee Information Student Loan Repayment Programs &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB18-087: Providing in-state tuition to refugees in Colorado<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-087|title=In-state Tuition Foreign Nationals Settled In Colorado {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n2016: Fenberg was the only Democrat to file for his party's 18th district primary on June 28. Incumbent Rollie Heath was term-limited and couldn't run for reelection. Fenberg ran unopposed in the primary and received 12,433 votes. On December 8, 2016, he faced off against Republican primary winner M. Peter Spraitz in the general election. Fenberg had been endorsed by the state branches of the AFL-CIO, [[Planned Parenthood]] and [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]] as well as Colorado Voters for Animals and Conservation Colorado.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/169954/steve-fenberg#.WKu63RIrJn4 |title= Steve Fenberg's Political Summary |location= Des Moines, Iowa |publisher= [[Project Vote Smart]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref> Fenberg coasted to a 59 point victory, the result of 67,799 votes,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_District_18 |title= Colorado State Senate District 18 |publisher= [[Ballotpedia]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref> more than any other senate candidate statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_elections,_2016 |title= Colorado State Senate elections, 2016 |publisher= [[Ballotpedia]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards & recognition==\n\n*Speaking Truth to Power Award, 2006 (presented by the [[AFL-CIO]])<ref name=\"AS\" />\n*Future Generations Act recognition, 2018 (presented by the Colorado Sportsmen's Caucus)\n*Legislator of the Year Award, 2018 (presented by the Colorado Trial Lawyer's Association)\n*Solar & Storage Champion of the Year, 2019 (presented by the Colorado Solar & Storage Association)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|SteveFenberg}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-co-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Holbert]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Majority Leader of the [[Colorado Senate]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{U.S. State Senate Floor Leaders|state=collapsed}}\n{{Current Colorado statewide political officials}}\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fenberg, Steve}}\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Steve Fenberg\n| image = Steve Fenberg.JPG\n| office = Majority Leader of the [[Colorado Senate]]\n| term_start = January 4, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Chris Holbert]]\n| successor = \n| state_senate1 = Colorado\n| district1 = 18th\n| term_start1 = January 11, 2017\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Rollie Heath]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|1|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Toledo, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Lindsay Urban\n| education = [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado, Boulder]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| website = {{url|stevefenberg.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Fenberg''' (born January 2, 1984) is an American [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician serving as a State Senator from [[Colorado]]. He has served in the state's 18th district since 2017.<ref name=\"CGA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradosenate.org/fenberg |title=Senator Steve Fenberg |location=[[Denver, Colorado]] |publisher=Colorado Senate Democrats |accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref> He currently serves as Senate Majority Leader.\n\n==Education==\nSenator Fenberg received his [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[Environmental Policy]] at the University of Colorado.<ref name =\"DC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/colorado-election-news/ci_30471306/steve-fenberg-state-senate-district-18 |title= Steve Fenberg: State Senate, District 18 |location=Boulder, Colorado |publisher=[[Daily Camera]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017|date= 2016-10-15 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA few years after graduating from CU, Fenberg founded New Era Colorado, a nonprofit organization dedicated engaging, educating, and training young people in the political process. The organization has registered hundreds of thousands of young people to vote in Colorado and successfully passed several pieces of legislation related to election reform, student debt, and climate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neweracolorado.org/about-us/#.WKum7xIrJn4 |title= New Leaders for a Generation |location=Denver, Colorado |publisher=New Era Colorado |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also served on the Board of Directors for ProgressNow, One Colorado Political Committee, and INVST Community Studies as well as the Boulder Housing Working Group and the city of Boulder Capital Improvement Taskforce.<ref name =\"DC\" /> Fenberg now serves as an Advisory Board member for the dZi Foundation, an international nonprofit providing development work in remote areas of Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dzi.org/who-we-are/teams/|title=Teams {{!}} dZi foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\nFenberg is part-owner of the Bread Bar, a cocktail bar in the historic town of [[Silver Plume, Colorado|Silver Plume]]. Bread Bar resides at the site of a historic bakery from the 1800's.<ref name=\"AS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stevefenberg.org/about-steve-2/ |title= About Steve |publisher= 2016 Fenberg State Senate |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>.\n\n==Policy positions==\n===Environment===\nAs an advocate of a statewide [[carbon tax]], Fenberg would also like to increase the [[renewable energy]] standards from 30% to 50% in the next 30 years.\n\nAs far as [[fracking]] is concerned, he acknowledges the risks involved and the need for tighter regulations but is a supporter of local control by communities.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite web |url= http://www.stevefenberg.org/issues/ |title= Current Legislation and Priorities |location=Boulder, Colorado |publisher=2016 Feinberg State Senate |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\nFenberg is [[United States pro-choice movement|pro-choice]] and supports same-sex marriage. He supports funding to expand access to comprehensive birth control.\n\n===Jobs & growth===\nFenberg believes in the right of workers to [[collective bargaining|collectively bargain]], strives for an increased minimum wage and sees the current requirements pertaining to sick days as inadequate.<ref name=\"SS\" />\n\n==Tenure (Colorado Senate)==\nFenberg has served as a member of the following committees:\n\n* Senate Agriculture, Natural Resources, and Energy Committee \n* State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee\n* Legislative Council\n* Executive Committee of the Legislative Council<ref name=\"CGA\" />\n\nAuthored/sponsored bills by Fenberg have focused on a variety of topics ranging from the easing of student debt to gerrymandering reform as well as the prohibition of [[conversion therapy|gay conversion therapy]].<ref name=\"SS\" /> The following bills are some of Fenberg's legislative accomplishments:\n\n=== Energy, Climate, and the Environment ===\n\n* SB19-181: Comprehensive oil & gas reforms to protect health & safety<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-181|title=Protect Public Welfare Oil And Gas Operations {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* SB19-236: Sunset of the Public Utilities Commission <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-236|title=Sunset Public Utilities Commission &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB18-009: Establishing the right of consumers to store their own energy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-009|title=Allow Electric Utility Customers Install Energy Storage Equipment {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* SB18-143: Parks and Wildlife Measures to Increase Revenue <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-143|title=Parks and Wildlife Measures to Increase Revenue &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Election Reform ===\n\n* SB19-235: Creating automatic voter registration<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-235|title=Automatic Voter Registration {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> \n* HB19-1278: Modifications to Uniform Election Code <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1278|title=Modifications to Uniform Election Code &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Human/Civil Rights & Mental Health ===\n\n* HB19-1129: Prohibiting gay conversion therapy on minors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1129|title=Prohibit Conversion Therapy for A Minor {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n* HB19-1266: Restore Voting Rights to Parolees <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1266|title=Restore Voting Rights Parolees &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* HB19-1280: Youth Mental Health Education and Suicide Prevention <ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1120|title=Youth Mental Health Education and Suicide Prevention &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\n=== Hemp & Marijuana ===\n\n* SB19-224: Sunset Regulated Marijuana<ref>{{cite web |url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-224|title=Sunset Regulated Marijuana &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* HB19-1028: Medical Marijuana Condition Autism <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb19-1028|title=Medical Marijuana Condition Autism &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB19-220: Creating statewide plan for hemp cultivation & regulation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-220|title=Hemp Regulation Alignment With 2018 Federal Farm Bill {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\n\n* SB19-002: Regulate Student Loan Servicers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-002|title=Regulate Student Education Loan Servicers &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref> \n* SB19-057: Employee Information Public Student Loan Repayment Programs <ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb19-057|title=Employee Information Student Loan Repayment Programs &#124; Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n* SB18-087: Providing in-state tuition to refugees in Colorado<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb18-087|title=In-state Tuition Foreign Nationals Settled In Colorado {{!}} Colorado General Assembly|website=leg.colorado.gov|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n2016: Fenberg was the only Democrat to file for his party's 18th district primary on June 28. Incumbent Rollie Heath was term-limited and couldn't run for reelection. Fenberg ran unopposed in the primary and received 12,433 votes. On December 8, 2016, he faced off against Republican primary winner M. Peter Spraitz in the general election. Fenberg had been endorsed by the state branches of the AFL-CIO, [[Planned Parenthood]] and [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]] as well as Colorado Voters for Animals and Conservation Colorado.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/169954/steve-fenberg#.WKu63RIrJn4 |title= Steve Fenberg's Political Summary |location= Des Moines, Iowa |publisher= [[Project Vote Smart]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref> Fenberg coasted to a 59 point victory, the result of 67,799 votes,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_District_18 |title= Colorado State Senate District 18 |publisher= [[Ballotpedia]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref> more than any other senate candidate statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_elections,_2016 |title= Colorado State Senate elections, 2016 |publisher= [[Ballotpedia]] |accessdate= 20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards & recognition==\n\n*Speaking Truth to Power Award, 2006 (presented by the [[AFL-CIO]])<ref name=\"AS\" />\n*Future Generations Act recognition, 2018 (presented by the Colorado Sportsmen's Caucus)\n*Legislator of the Year Award, 2018 (presented by the Colorado Trial Lawyer's Association)\n*Solar & Storage Champion of the Year, 2019 (presented by the Colorado Solar & Storage Association)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|SteveFenberg}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-co-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Holbert]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Majority Leader of the [[Colorado Senate]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{U.S. State Senate Floor Leaders|state=collapsed}}\n{{Current Colorado statewide political officials}}\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fenberg, Steve}}\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "name_user": "Blizzardwind", "label": "safe", "comment": "added senate district links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Fenberg"}
